SIMPLE: enroll
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Enroll
<hw>En*roll"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Enrolled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Enrolling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Pref. <ets>en-</ets>
+ <ets>roll</ets>: cf. F. <ets>enr⟦ocir⟧ler</ets>; pref. <ets>en-</ets>
(L. <ets>in</ets>) + <ets>r⟦ocir⟧le</ets> roll or register. See
<er>Roll</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>enrol</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To insert in a roil; to
register or enter in a list or catalogue or on rolls of court; hence, to
record; to insert in records; to leave in writing; <as>as, to
<ex>enroll</ex> men for service; to <ex>enroll</ex> a decree or a
law</as>; also, reflexively, to enlist.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An unwritten law of common right, so engraven in the hearts of our
ancestors, and by them so constantly enjoyed and claimed, as that it
needed not <qex>enrolling</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the citizen capable of bearing arms <qex>enrolled</qex>
themselves.</q> <rj><qau>Prescott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To envelop; to inwrap; to involve.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>enrollee</ent>⟦br⟧
